<body>
    <h1>#57_Security and Compliance Strategy and Approach</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h1 id=3D"id-#57_SecurityandComplianceStrategyandApproach-Identitya=
ndAccessManagement(IAM)Approach"><strong>Identity and Access Management (IA=
M) Approach</strong></h1>
<p>As part of the Voyager implementation, the current state IAM process wil=
l be reviewed and refined during IAM workshops to gather requirements for t=
he future state vision for IAM for Oracle Cloud. Leading practices will be =
leveraged to help facilitate automation wherever possible to support effici=
encies within the process. As part of this implementation and transition fr=
om legacy systems, there will be data clean up and reconciliation to prepar=
e current environment Identity/User data to be loaded and migrated to Oracl=
e Cloud.</p>
<p>Ascension currently utilizes the following tools to support IAM processe=
s:</p>
<p>=E2=97=8F&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; SailPoint to support user provision=
ing for some enterprise systems</p>
<p>=E2=97=8F&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ServiceNow to support ticketing req=
uests for user access</p>
<p>=E2=97=8F&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Microsoft Entra ID to facilitate id=
entity management and SSO</p>
<p>Once requirements are gathered related to IAM, a solution document will =
be prepared and supporting technical specifications will be developed. Comp=
onents of this design will include SailPoint workflows, connectors, tasks, =
workgroups, roles, and policies to support the future state process design =
for IAM. Once designs are approved, SailPoint will be configured and tested=
 as part of SIT and UAT based on an established IAM Testing Strategy. Addit=
ional outputs from this workstream will be IAM Software Code, IAM Unit Test=
 Case Documentation, and Test Case Evidence, Traceability Matrix, Regressio=
n Testing, and <span style=3D"background-color: rgb(254,222,200);">Disaster=
 Recovery Testing</span>. As processes and design are refined, IAM Solution=
 Go-Live Plan and Lessons Learned Document will be developed and delivered.=
</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-#57_SecurityandComplianceStrategyandApproach-4.1UsernameConven=
tionandSingleSign-On(SSO)"><strong>4.1</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong=
>Username Convention and Single Sign-On (SSO)</strong></h2>
<p>To support SSO integration with Ascension=E2=80=99s Enterprise Identity =
Provider Entra ID, the convention for usernames in Oracle Cloud will be the=
 user principle name (UPN) address of the users for both Non-Production and=
 Production environments.</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-#57_SecurityandComplianceStrategyandApproach-4.2PrivilegedAcce=
ssManagement(PAM)=E2=80=93CyberArk"><strong>4.2</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp=
; <strong>Privileged Access Management (PAM) =E2=80=93 CyberArk</strong></h=
2>
<p>Ascension currently utilizes CyberArk to monitor privileged accounts. Du=
ring the Voyager implementation, CyberArk will be used for check-in &amp; c=
heck-out of passwords for highly privileged system accounts/admin accounts =
in both Non-Production and Production environments.</p>
<p>The convention of usernames for admin accounts in Oracle cloud should ma=
tch with the Directory services account. A random string is created by the =
Directory Services team for admin accounts and will be used as the username=
 for admin accounts in Oracle applications. To identify these random string=
s as admin accounts in Oracle applications, the first name or last name of =
the user is updated to include DS.&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-#57_SecurityandComplianceStrategyandApproach-4.3UsertoRoleMapp=
ingApproach"><strong>4.3</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>User to Role =
Mapping Approach</strong></h2>
<p>In support of testing cycles throughout the implementation, users will n=
eed to be mapped to Oracle Cloud application security roles to control what=
 they are testing. As documented in the<a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"h=
ttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1OCfh7nRUukibz60y2n2wjHovuw5fGDG4/edit#he=
ading=3Dh.25b2l0r" rel=3D"nofollow"> <strong>2.1.2 Configure, Prototype, an=
d Test</strong></a> section, based on the testing cycle, different approach=
es will be taken for user to role mapping to facilitate productive test cyc=
les. As testing cycles progress towards UAT, user to role mapping should be=
 production-like to facilitate both SOD analysis and end-to-end testing. In=
 alignment with application security guiding principles, the following are =
best practices for user to role mapping:</p>
<p>=E2=97=8F&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>Utilize the concept of =E2=
=80=9Cleast privileged=E2=80=9D access =E2=80=93 </strong>Users should be g=
ranted the least amount of access which allows them to do their job</p>
<p>=E2=97=8F&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>Enforce Segregation of Duties (SOD=
) =E2=80=93 </strong>Users should not be assigned roles which create SOD ri=
sks</p>
<p>=E2=97=8F&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>Standardization =E2=80=93 <=
/strong>Where possible, identify criteria/data that can be used to group en=
d users (i.e., job codes or departments). This can greatly decrease the eff=
ort of user to role mapping and increase consistency among end users</p>
<p>Ascension Identity and Access management lead will be the champion of th=
e user to role mapping exercise and serve as a liaison between the implemen=
tation team and business leads. User to role mapping activities will commen=
ce once role designs have been finalized and a draft will be established pr=
ior to SIT1. A standardized template will be utilized to capture user to ro=
le mapping. An additional input which will be leveraged as part of this exe=
rcise is existing user to responsibility listings from legacy applications.=
 Regardless of the process established for provisioning access to end users=
 as part of the IAM work mentioned in section 4. <em><strong>Identity and A=
ccess Management (IAM) Approach</strong></em>, user to role mapping is a cr=
itical success factor for the Voyager implementation.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-#57_SecurityandComplianceStrategyandApproach-4.4UserProvisioni=
ng"><strong>4.4</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>User Provisioning</str=
ong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"id-#57_SecurityandComplianceStrategyandApproach-4.4.1Usercreation=
andRoleProvisioningforVoyagerImplementation"><strong>4.4.1</strong> &nbsp; =
&nbsp; <strong>User creation and Role Provisioning for Voyager Implementati=
on</strong></h3>
<p>As part of the Voyager implementation, the SaaS environments are spun up=
 by the Ascension Tech team and Ascension security team owns access to Orac=
le pods initially. After the Deloitte security team is on-boarded into the =
instances, the security and controls for the environment is implemented as =
per the RACI and the details are captured in the Environment Checklist form=
. Necessary Approvals on the Environment Checklist form is obtained from th=
e Ascension Security &amp; Compliance, post which the environment will be r=
eleased for individual requests. For access requests in Sprint environments=
, the requests are being handled via a User Access Request Form (UARF) crea=
ted for each environment and hosted on Ascension GDrive and a process has b=
een established for program leadership to alert the security team if certai=
n team members are no longer supporting the Voyager implementation so they =
can be de-provisioned in a timely manner. Users are only being granted acce=
ss to Oracle environments once they have been officially onboarded onto the=
 engagement. Access to create additional user accounts (within the security=
 console) is limited to the security teams in support of the Voyager implem=
entation.&nbsp;</p>
<p></p>
    </div>
</body>
